




TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Simple Forward Algorithm to Solve General Dynamic Lot Sizing Models with n Periods in 0(n log n) or 0(n) Time
AU  - Federgruen, Awi
AU  - Tzur, Michal
Y1  - 1991/08/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.37.8.909
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.37.8.909
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 909
EP  - 925
VL  - 37
IS  - 8
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper is concerned with the general dynamic lot size model, or (generalized) Wagner-Whitin model. Let n denote the number of periods into which the planning horizon is divided. We describe a simple forward algorithm which solves the general model in 0(n log n) time and 0(n) space, as opposed to the well-known shortest path algorithm advocated over the last 30 years with 0(n2) time. A linear, i.e., 0(n)-time and space algorithm is obtained for two important special cases: (a) models without speculative motives for carrying stock, i.e., where in each interval of time the per unit order cost increases by less than the cost of carrying a unit in stock; (b) models with nondecreasing setup costs. We also derive conditions for the existence of monotone optimal policies and relate these to known (planning horizon and other) results from the literature.
AB  - This paper is concerned with the general dynamic lot size model, or (generalized) Wagner-Whitin model. Let n denote the number of periods into which the planning horizon is divided. We describe a simple forward algorithm which solves the general model in 0(n log n) time and 0(n) space, as opposed to the well-known shortest path algorithm advocated over the last 30 years with 0(n2) time. A linear, i.e., 0(n)-time and space algorithm is obtained for two important special cases: (a) models without speculative motives for carrying stock, i.e., where in each interval of time the per unit order cost increases by less than the cost of carrying a unit in stock; (b) models with nondecreasing setup costs. We also derive conditions for the existence of monotone optimal policies and relate these to known (planning horizon and other) results from the literature.
